In November 2024, a motion to establish an affordable housing acquisition fund in Ottawa failed to pass at the city’s planning and housing committee. The proposal, introduced by College Ward Councillor Laine Johnson, would have redirected surplus revenue from the city’s vacant unit tax into a fund dedicated to preserving at-risk affordable housing. Johnson argued that Ottawa’s current housing plan focused too narrowly on new construction, ignoring the ongoing loss of existing affordable units. She warned that without a strategy to acquire and protect aging rental stock, the city was “bailing out a leaky rowboat.”
<div class="break"> </div>
Despite support from tenant advocates and several councillors — including Ariel Troster, Jeff Leiper, and Riley Brockington — the motion was voted down eight to four. City staff and senior officials opposed the plan, citing fears it could jeopardize eligibility for federal and provincial housing funds, which are tied to aggressive construction targets. They also raised concerns about rising market prices, renovation costs, and the risk of diverting limited municipal resources away from shovel-ready builds.
<div class="break"> </div>

Supporters of the fund pointed to success stories in cities like Toronto and Vancouver, and to local pilots like the Ottawa Community Land Trust, which had already acquired two properties using a mix of municipal support, community bonds, and donations. However, city leadership insisted that until more federal guidance was available on the Canada Rental Protection Fund — a $1.5 billion national acquisition initiative still under development — Ottawa would stick with its current approach. 
